  </music>
</mei>

<!--
VOICING PLAN:
- This piece is strongly bimodal: oscillates E(I) and B(V) as primary poles, with
  A(IV) and C#m(vi) as secondary colors. Chromatically annotated Eb throughout
  the original is consistently interpreted as B(V) — the dominant — which makes
  musical sense as an anticipatory leading tone gesture.
- Bb in bar 5 also → B(V): nearest diatonic chord.
- C#7 in bar 9 → C#m(vi): diatonic substitution.
- F#m(ii) appears only in bar 11 for color variety.
- LH voicings: E = E2-B2-E3-G#3 (P5+P4+m3), B = B2-F#3-B3-D#4 (P4+P4+M3),
  A = A2-E3-A3-C#4 (P5+P4+m3), C#m = C#2-G#2-C#3-E3 (P5+P4+m3).
- 2/4 meter means one chord per beat maximum — the harp plays quarter-note voicings
  mostly, with the occasional half-note for sustained bars.

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- E→B (recurring): RH G#4-B4 → F#4-B4 or B4-D#5. Common B held or B steps D#.
- Bar 4 C#m: RH opens with arpeggio feel E4-C#5 then G#4-E5 (expanding outward).
- Bar 9 E→C#m: RH G#4-B4 → A4-C#5, inner voice B4→A4 (step down) + outer G#4→C#5 (4th up).
- Bar 12: E full triad RH (3 notes) for first time — marks the final approach.
- Bar 14: LH spans E2-B3 (a 12th) — widest span in the piece, climactic final resonance.

TEXTURE ARC:
- Pickup + mm. 0-4: Thin 2/4 opening — 2-note RH, 3-note LH. E oscillates with B.
- mm. 5-8: Bridge — high D#5-F#5 in bar 5 (highest point), A(IV) color bars 7-8.
- mm. 9-11: Inner development — C#m color (bar 9), F#m (bar 11), minor inflections.
- mm. 12-14: Final approach — bar 12 adds 3-note RH, bar 13 mirrors, bar 14 widest LH.
-->
